messages.message: (Sorry on a train rn) @naveen yeah one of the things we are going to think about, once we get to focusing on usability, is what tools and information can we give them that is accessible to them and their knowledge. Certain models have different sorts of parameters and output that we can leverage to provide debuggability

tbh debuggability is something really important, and really hard in this context. It’s something to think about (we’re especially looking at wandb.ai (http://wandb.ai) for this). But definitely no quick answer here.

I see. I have a question about the intended user experience here. Is the goal:
1. to provide a set of specific models (pre-trained W2, 1099, and 1040 models) which our customers can then tweak/update using our tools, or
2. to provide a general set of tooling with which our customers can build/train their own models without in-depth knowledge of how DL works (ie. NatWest wants to build a model that understands their internal documents)
Or is it maybe a mix of both?

Initial goal over the next few months is to experiment with these models and processes to see what works and what makes sense, and then the goal is that we would be able to enable both of your points above over time.
Got it, thanks! I’m excited to see this come to life :slightly_smiling_face:
